    nextMove: "Run it like an incident, publish it like a practice: (1) decompose the claim into its premises and grade each — consolidation pressure: RIGHT (two acquisitions); model providers absorbing orchestration: PARTIALLY RIGHT (their stacks grew, but as one option among several); category death in 18 months: WRONG (the leader tripled — network effects and switching costs outran platform absorption); the timing: overconfident by construction (18-month category-death calls need extraordinary evidence — 053's razor applied to your own demo); (2) price the advice's cost honestly — what the customer lost (time-to-capability on workflows the competitor shipped, priced with 043's attribution honesty: some of the gap is the tool, some isn't) and what the advice PROTECTED (the two acquired platforms' customers ate 064-scale migrations — the read wasn't costless-wrong); (3) extract the process lessons — the forecast conflated directional pressure with terminal outcome (consolidation ≠ death), ignored the survivor scenario (base rates: category leaders survive consolidations that kill the middle), and issued binary advice ('don't build') where portfolio advice fit ('build with 094's exit drills'); (4) publish to the audience the original claim had — the sponsor gets the one-pager: claim, verdict, cost, lesson, and the patched process (099's own format); unprompted disclosure of a forgotten miss is the highest-yield credibility purchase available (032's truth economics, applied to yourself); (5) patch the ledger's process — category-death claims now require survivor-scenario analysis, advice attached to forecasts carries hedged structure by default (092's contracts, for recommendations), and the resolution review is calendared, not conscience-triggered.",
