  modelAnswer:
    "The ledger called; answer it like an incident, because that's what an unexamined miss is — 027's watermelon running on your own forecasting record, green until audited. Decompose before narrating: the claim bundled four things, and they resolved differently. Consolidation pressure: right — two independents got acquired, exactly the mechanism you named. Model providers absorbing orchestration: half-right — their stacks grew into real options, but as competitors in the category, not as its graveyard. Category death in eighteen months: wrong — the leader tripled, because network effects and switching costs outran platform absorption (the survivor scenario your forecast never priced; base rates say consolidation kills the middle and often feeds the leader). And the advice — 'don't build on the independents' — was binary where portfolio fit: 'build with exit drills' (094's discipline existed for exactly this) would have captured the upside and hedged the risk you correctly saw.\n\nPrice it honestly, both directions: the customer lost time-to-capability on workflows their competitor shipped (attributed with 043's discipline — some of that gap is the tool, some is the competitor's execution), and the advice also protected them from the two acquired platforms' fates — their customers ate 064-scale migrations. Wrong-with-partial-cover is the honest verdict; round it neither up nor down.\n\nThen the move that matters: publish to the claim's original audience, unprompted. The sponsor forgot; that's precisely why the disclosure compounds — a one-pager: claim, verdict, cost, lessons, patch. Every incentive says bury it; the practice says the buried miss is a loan against the next big read, at compounding interest. And patch the process, specifically: category-death claims now require survivor-scenario analysis; forecast-attached advice defaults to hedged structure (092's logic, for recommendations); resolution reviews are calendared. The last line of the one-pager is the whole discipline: this practice reports its losses on schedule — which is the only reason its wins should move your decisions.",
