    nextMove: "Build the thesis from the migration's mechanism, not from headlines: (1) trace the solved layers — raw model capability is compounding on lab capex (not the customer's constraint to solve), serving economics industrialized (038/091/095: cost curves falling on schedule where competition holds), platform and integration matured into known patterns (the 080/085 estate is buildable with discipline); (2) name where it binds now and next — the evidence across 016–089 points one direction: the constraint is migrating from CAPABILITY to VERIFICATION-AND-TRUST — the gap between what models can do and what organizations can safely, measurably, accountably LET them do (evals that keep pace with capability [073/088], oversight that means something [089], calibrated confidence in autonomous work [077/083], and the human judgment to govern it [097's talent tape saying the same thing in job postings]); the binding constraint in 24 months is not making agents capable — it's making organizations able to absorb agent capability at the rate it arrives; (3) allocate to the thesis — next year's dollar goes to the absorption stack: measurement infrastructure (the eval estate as a first-class asset), trust machinery (observability, oversight quality, red lines with teeth), and judgment capital (the people and playbooks that govern autonomy — this bank's own wager, named); (4) attach the falsifiers, dated — 'if agent-autonomy incidents DON'T become the industry's limiting news cycle within 18 months, if enterprises' deployment velocity keeps pace with model releases without absorption investment, if 097's tape shows evals/oversight roles declining rather than compounding — the thesis is wrong and capability (or its cost) was still the constraint'; (5) shape it per room — the board gets the allocation with the markers calendared into QBRs; the panel gets the same thesis plus its honest tension (the lab's job is moving the capability frontier; the industry's constraint is absorbing it — and the candidate who can hold both is the one they're hiring for).",
